Ebonyi State recorded partial compliance to the sit-at-home order declared by the Indigenous People of Biafra(IPOB). Banks and most filling stations in the state capital, Abakalili were shut down in the state as result. IPOB issued the order to be observed on the court appearance dates of its Leader, Nnamdi Kanu who is being prosecuted by the Federal Government on allegations of terrorism and treason. Many roads had scanty human and vehicular movement in the morning but it later picked up in the afternoon. None of the banks in the city opened for business.   Ahmed Musa donates N100m to 5,000 widows, others in Plateau     Erigga asks about ‘Yahoo’ rulers’ penalty over EFCC’s…     How to check rising prices of diesel, cooking gas –…   Few customers were however seen making use of the Automated mobile banking machine, ATM. Eateries, malls, markets and other shops and businesses were in full swing. Schools in the city especially private schools also were in session. Commercial motorcycle and tricycle operators operated in the city. Transport companies like Peace Mass Transit did not operate to other states but some of them ferries passengers to other towns within the state. Government offices were equally open as at the time Our Reporter monitored the exercise. Security agencies petalled the city to ward off any form of attack by dissidents who might try to enforce the order.